tweets.text: Hello everyone! My name is Norbert @norbertdelangen and I'll be sharing JS related topics this week. Exited to be here!
I do consultancy @xebia and currently do full-stack JS for @wehkamp I've worked for @heineken @hema @vwpfs @rtlnl
I love (and share info about): everything GUI & UX, react, css-modules, performance, webpack, styleguides / component libraries.
I'd like to thank @operatino for this opportunity, and @ramonvictor for being a great host last week. If you want to know more about me...

My Meetup: https://t.co/KZGvH5HfGD
My LinkedIn: https://t.co/TkH6dU3yq3
I think it's a way to create complete GUI components that's better then global CSS. https://t.co/Nu2XuI91lu

quoted_status.text: @LocalSourceNL What are your thoughts on CSS in JS?

tweets.text: @jitendravyas I'm not convinced it the absolute best solution, but I've worked with CSS-modules and found it very very useful.
@jitendravyas It does come with a cost: it adds more tooling complexity. Consider if your team be able deal this this before adopting.
Most api-services are microservices developed in product teams. Most in scala, some in .netCore, some in NodeJS. https://t.co/uWd1d3HWVo

quoted_status.text: @LocalSourceNL Are you building Node.js API's there as well? Tell us more about your current project.

tweets.text: @LocalSourceNL The team I work in, works on the SSR and clientside code for @wehkamp Product Overview & Detail. Our current longterm goal...
@LocalSourceNL ...is migrating away from AngularJS on the clientside, and getting everything rendered isomophic|universal with React.
@LocalSourceNL SSR is already achieved with React. We're also looking into splitting the site up into microsites and creating a component...
@LocalSourceNL ...library for all these microsites. Goal is to be able to scale and maintain these microservices and sites independently.
For my current project, a few thirdparty scripts had a dependency on jQuery. Which led to developers using jQuery because it was there...
Using jQuery in combination with Angular shouldn't be necessary! Force Angular to ignore jQuery with `ng-jq` https://t.co/ob1pW8mHp6
@operatino Yes, we do! We use `ReactDOMServer.renderToStaticMarkup` right now, because we do not have react clientside yet.
Question: Are you using ES201#, if so what stage? I have found Object spread to be immensely useful! (stage2)
Yes, it's possible: by bootstrapping angular manually, you may provide options. https://t.co/GJizCYswKI https://t.co/SjBqyKM6kl

quoted_status.text: @LocalSourceNL do you use any UI libraries (main job, pet-projects)? If yes, which one could you recommend for new projects?

tweets.text: @LocalSourceNL ...facing websites, I recommend NOT using one, pick some utilities from them maybe. Admin panel like things, most will do.
@MLarchanka @LocalSourceNL I liked Foundation over Bootstrap. Would I need one right now, I'd look for something using react + css-modules.
@MLarchanka What have you used, and what were the pros and cons you found?
@LocalSourceNL doing things in templates is rather normal in Angular, not a fan of it myself either.

@operatino @LocalSourceNL We don't do caching of pages. We're looking into component caching.
I wish I could say we do streamed rendering, but we don't. It's on our roadmap. I hear https://t.co/I17rfwCJ4P can. https://t.co/E7mKAPDUKB

quoted_status.text: @LocalSourceNL do you use streamed rendering? or just a default renderer, that returns everything when it's completely ready?

tweets.text: @LocalSourceNL It'd be a great performance boost for us, currently we wait for all services to result data, and only then start rendering.
@LocalSourceNL I think with streamed rendering we could start rendering til we hit a UI part that needs data. Anyone has experience with it?
